Tuesday A.M. 
Dearest Enat:
I'm so grateful for those two letters out of your heart. I'm run raggd here and am very eary, but I want to write something without any more delay. 
First, I must say that Dr. Sealock's secretary will quit at the end of this year, as I think I wrote you, she is now married & plans to being raising a family after this year. A sensible, planning young woman, certainly. I will try for the job, & Sealock is very much a friend, so is Mrs. S, It could possibly be landed. But listen to this, dearest and one of the best of all Girls! Think of your present general situation like this: YOu are not definitely cut off from all that is dear to you, nothing is cut off. Your ships are not burned behind you. This si not hte beginning of a strange new life by yoruself. You are only away going to school, just as Hiddy is. Yours is an educational institution as mu9ch as hers, & it is bigger, more complex. I do not think you will necessarily stay in the 

